Author:
Vol / Page:  14
Edition:
Quote:  In 1862 two miners suffering terrible hardships made their famous gold discovery in the Molyneux River below the junction of the Kawarau and Clutha Rivers, where the town of Cromwell now stands, and after several months of scratching around the crevices and river-bed beaches with pick, shovel, tin dish and cradle, returned to Dunedin with 87lb. weight of gold;  these two men were Messrs. Hartly and Riley.
